<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-geometry-of-the-gradient">
  <title>Geometry of the gradient</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret the gradient as perpendicular to level curves and level surfaces.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the gradient to describe tangent planes and normal vectors.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Connect geometric properties of the gradient to constrained motion along curves and surfaces.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction will go here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>

    <li>
      <p>
        Recall that the directional derivative can be written as
        <me>
          \pdv{f}{\uv{u}} = \Grad f \cdot \uv{u}.
        </me>
        If this directional derivative is zero, then <m>\uv{u}</m> must be perpendicular to <m>\Grad f</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus any direction in which the function does not change must be orthogonal to the gradient.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A level curve of <m>f</m> is defined by
        <me>
          f(x,y)=k.
        </me>
        If a point moves along this curve, the value of <m>f</m> does not change.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let <m>\bv{r}(t)</m> parametrize the curve. Then
        <me>
          f(\bv{r}(t))=k.
        </me>
        Differentiating with respect to <m>t</m>:
        <me>
          \dv{f}{t} = \Grad f(\bv{r}(t)) \cdot \bv{r}'(t) = 0.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Since <m>\bv{r}'(t)</m> is tangent to the level curve, we conclude that <m>\Grad f</m> is perpendicular to the level curve.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        In three dimensions, a level surface is given by
        <me>
          f(x,y,z)=k.
        </me>
        The same reasoning shows that
        <me>
          \Grad f
        </me>
        is perpendicular to the surface.
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus the gradient provides a natural normal vector to any level surface.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        This allows us to write the equation of the tangent plane to the surface <m>z=f(x,y)</m> at the point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> in vector form:
        <me>
          z = f(\bv{r}_0) + \Grad f(\bv{r}_0)\cdot(\bv{r}-\bv{r}_0).
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Rearranging,
        <me>
          \pdv{f}{x}(x-x_0)+\pdv{f}{y}(y-y_0)-1(z-z_0)=0.
        </me>
        The vector
        <me>
          \qty(\pdv{f}{x},\pdv{f}{y},-1)
        </me>
        is normal to the tangent plane.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        More generally, if a surface is defined implicitly by
        <me>
          F(x,y,z)=0,
        </me>
        then <m>\Grad F</m> is normal to the surface.
        This gives us the tangent plane equation:
        <me>
          \Grad F(x_0,y_0,z_0)\cdot\qty(x-x_0,y-y_0,z-z_0)=0.
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Why does the normal direction matter?
        In physics and computer graphics, surface normals determine how light reflects.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>